        output='Based on the provided filing excerpts, here is how Starship\'s role in deploying next-generation satellites and the Space segment\'s support of the Connectivity segment are detailed:\n\n### **Starship\'s Role in Deploying Next-Generation Starlink Satellites**\n*   **Massive Scale for V3 Broadband Satellites:** Starship is expected to begin deploying next-generation V3 satellites in the second half of 2026. Each V3 satellite offers 1 Tbps of downlink capacity. A single Starship launch will be capable of deploying up to **60 V3 satellites**, representing a **twenty-fold increase** in downlink capacity deployed per launch compared to the Falcon 9.\n*   **Accelerating the Mobile Constellation:** To expand Starlink Mobile (satellite-to-mobile connectivity) and eliminate global "dead zones," Starship is anticipated to deploy approximately **50 mobile satellites per launch**, drastically increasing capacity and accelerating the rollout of the next-generation mobile constellation.\n*   **Lower Technical Barriers for LEO Deployment:** The filing clarifies that achieving full reusability of Starship’s upper stage and mastering in-orbit refueling are **not required** to deploy V3 and V2 Mobile satellites to Low-Earth Orbit (LEO). \n*   **Advanced Deployment Systems:** To handle mass deployment at scale, SpaceX plans to leverage a **"PEZ dispenser" system** (an integrated payload deployment system for Starship). Combined with the proven launch survivability of existing Starlink satellites (which achieve 99.9% uptime), this will substantially reduce the risks associated with in-orbit assembly and massive deployments.\n\n### **How the Space Segment Supports the Connectivity Segment**\n*   **Strategic Capacity Allocation:** The Space segment allocates a "significant amount of launch capacity" directly to the Connectivity segment to scale the Starlink Broadband and Mobile constellations. \n*   **Internal Accounting & Revenue Recognition:** Launches dedicated to deploying internal Starlink satellites **do not generate revenue** for the Space segment. Instead, the associated launch costs are capitalized within the Connectivity segment and depreciated over time. The Space segment only recognizes revenue from third-party customer launches.\n*   **Foundational Strategic Value:** Because internal Starlink launches are excluded from its top-line numbers, the Space segment shows "relatively lower revenue scale and revenue growth." However, the filing emphasizes that the Space segment\'s financial results do not reflect its **"foundational strategic value."** Its unmatched ability to launch mass to orbit at a low cost serves as the company\'s "foundational competitive advantage," directly bolstering and underpinning the growth of the Connectivity segment.\n*   **Symbiotic Technical Hurdles:** The Space segment\'s launch capabilities and the Connectivity segment\'s satellite expertise are deeply intertwined. The company notes it has already solved many technical hurdles to evolving connectivity satellites into AI compute satellites by leveraging Starlink\'s existing operational capabilities (e.g., constellation-scale management, autonomous operations, and inter-satellite laser communications) alongside the Space segment\'s launch infrastructure.',
