    final_answer='## Part 1: Connectivity Revenue as a Percentage of Consolidated Q1 2026 Revenue\n\nBased on the segment revenue breakdown in the SpaceX S-1 (filed May 20, 2026), for the three months ended March 31, 2026:\n\n| Segment | Q1 2026 Revenue ($M) |\n|---|---|\n| Space | $619 |\n| **Connectivity** | **$3,257** |\n| AI | $818 |\n| **Total Consolidated** | **$4,694** |\n\n**Calculation:** $3,257 / $4,694 = **69.39%**\n\nConnectivity revenue represented **69.39%** of consolidated Q1 2026 revenue. (Note: All figures reflect the retrospectively recast consolidated entity, including xAI and X Holdings.)\n\n---\n\n## Part 2: Quarters of Starship R&D Spending Equal to One Year of FY2025 Connectivity Capex\n\nKey figures from the filing:\n\n| Metric | Amount ($M) |\n|---|---|\n| FY2025 Connectivity Capital Expenditures (full year) | $4,178 |\n| Q1 2026 Starship R&D Spending (one quarter) | $930 |\n\n**Calculation:** $4,178 / $930 = **4.49 quarters**\n\nIt would take approximately **4.49 quarters** (~1.12 years) of current-quarter Starship R&D spending to equal one full year of FY2025 Connectivity capex.\n\n---\n\n## Part 3: Which Metric Better Captures Cross-Segment Dependency?\n\n**The Starship R&D-to-Connectivity capex ratio (4.49×) is the superior metric for capturing cross-segment dependency.** Here is the analytical reasoning:\n\n### Why the Capex/R&D Ratio Is More Informative\n\n1. **It directly links investment flows between segments.** The ratio connects the Space segment\'s R&D spend on Starship (the launch vehicle) to the Connectivity segment\'s capital investment in satellite and ground infrastructure. This is the operational nexus where the two segments physically intersect—Starship exists, in significant part, to deploy Starlink satellites.\n\n2. **The filing\'s own accounting confirms this.** The S-1 explicitly states that when the Space segment launches Starlink satellites internally, **no inter-segment revenue is recognized**. Instead, launch costs are **capitalized within the Connectivity segment\'s PP&E** and depreciated over time. This means the true economic relationship between segments is captured through investment and cost flows—not through revenue. A revenue-concentration metric systematically understates the Space segment\'s role because its internal contribution to Connectivity is invisible in top-line figures.\n\n3. **It reflects bidirectional dependency.** Connectivity depends on Starship for next-gen V3 satellite deployment (60 satellites per launch, a 20× improvement over Falcon 9), while Starship\'s development is partly justified by the need to scale the Connectivity constellation. The revenue-percentage metric is unidirectional—it only shows how much the consolidated entity depends on Connectivity\'s top line.\n\n4. **The filing itself warns against relying on segment revenue.** The S-1 explicitly cautions that the Space segment\'s financial results "do not reflect the foundational strategic value that it provides to us in bolstering the growth of our Connectivity and AI segments."\n\n### Why Revenue Concentration Is Less Useful\n\nThe 69.39% figure measures **revenue concentration risk**, not cross-segment dependency. It tells us the company is heavily reliant on Connectivity subscription revenue, but it says nothing about *how* the segments enable each other operationally. A company could have 69% revenue concentration in a segment that is entirely self-contained with zero dependency on other segments.\n\n### Summary\n\n| Metric | Value | What It Measures | Cross-Segment Insight |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Connectivity % of Revenue | 69.39% | Revenue concentration | Low — unidirectional, masks inter-segment flows |\n| Starship R&D / Connectivity Capex | 4.49 quarters | Investment interdependency | **High** — captures the capital linkage between launch infrastructure and satellite deployment |\n\n---\n\n**Sources:**\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026)"\n    }\n  ]\n}',
